## Lakebase Health Check Schema Resolution Fix — 2026-05-12

### Context
Settings → Lakebase Connection reported "schema 'ontobricks_graph' does not exist yet" even
though the schema was created by a Digital Twin build. Root cause: the health check was reading
the schema name only from `graph_engine_config.schema`, while the build pipeline resolves the
schema via `resolve_lakebase_graph_schema()` — which first checks `RegistryCfg.schema` (the
middle segment of the registry Volume UC triplet `catalog.schema.volume`) and overrides the
config value with it. When a registry Volume schema is configured, the two paths diverged and
the health check always queried for the wrong schema name.

### Changes

1. `src/back/objects/domain/SettingsService.py`
   - `graph_engine_lakebase_health_result`: capture `domain` from `_resolve_context` (was
     discarded with `_`).
   - Replace `validate_graph_schema(schema_raw or default_schema())` with a call to
     `resolve_lakebase_graph_schema(domain, settings, schema_raw)` so the health check uses
     the exact same schema resolution logic as the build pipeline (RegistryCfg.schema wins,
     falls back to `graph_engine_config.schema`, then to the default).
   - Added a safe fallback: if `resolve_lakebase_graph_schema` itself raises, fall back to
     `validate_graph_schema` to avoid crashing the probe entirely.

### Modified files
- `src/back/objects/domain/SettingsService.py`

### Test results
- `tests/test_lakebase_flat_store.py` — 15 passed
- `tests/test_graphdb_factory.py` — 15 passed, 1 skipped
- `tests/test_graph_engine_config.py` — 37 passed (1 pre-existing unrelated failure in
  `TestGraphEngineUcCatalogs::test_returns_sorted_catalogs` due to bad mock path for
  `DatabricksAuth.DatabricksAuth`, not related to this change)

